<DocsLayout title="Git & Code Quality" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Git & Code Quality</h1>

  <p>
    Your code is a contribution to the lab's collective knowledge. Supervisors need to
    review it, lab members may build on it, and your future self will need to understand
    it. Git is the tool that makes all of this possible — start using it from the very
    first line of code, not as an afterthought before submission.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-accent-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
    </svg>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Learning resources:</strong> the
      <a href="https://git-scm.com/book" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Pro Git book</a>
      is free and comprehensive.
      <a href="https://missing.csail.mit.edu/2020/version-control/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">MIT's version control lecture</a>
      is an excellent one-hour introduction to the underlying model.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Setup ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="setup">Repository Setup</h2>

  <p>
    Create a <strong>private</strong> GitHub repository at the start of your project
    and add your co-supervisors as collaborators (Settings → Collaborators, role: Write).
    Never make an AIRLab project repository public without explicit permission.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="westworld — project root"
    code={`# Initialise a new repository
git init
git branch -M main

# Connect to GitHub (create the repo on github.com first)
git remote add origin git@github.com:youruser/my_project.git

# First commit
git add .gitignore README.md Dockerfile requirements.txt
git commit -m "chore: initial project scaffold"
git push -u origin main`}
  />

  <p>Configure your identity on Westworld (only needed once):</p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`git config --global user.name "First Last"
git config --global user.email "firstname.lastname@mail.polimi.it"
git config --global init.defaultBranch main`}
  />

  <!-- ── Branching ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="branching">Branching Strategy</h2>

  <p>
    Keep <code>main</code> stable and always working. Do all active development on
    feature branches, and merge back only when the work is complete and tested.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# Create a branch for a new experiment or feature
git switch -c feat/attention-head-ablation

# ... work, commit often ...
git add src/models/attention.py
git commit -m "feat: add multi-head attention ablation variant"

# Merge back into main when ready
git switch main
git merge --no-ff feat/attention-head-ablation
git push origin main

# Delete the branch after merging
git branch -d feat/attention-head-ablation`}
  />

  <p>
    Use short, descriptive branch names with a prefix:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Prefix</th><th>Use for</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>feat/</code></td><td>New features or experiments</td><td><code>feat/rotary-embeddings</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>fix/</code></td><td>Bug fixes</td><td><code>fix/dataloader-shuffle</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>exp/</code></td><td>Exploratory experiments</td><td><code>exp/lr-schedule-sweep</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>docs/</code></td><td>Documentation only</td><td><code>docs/update-readme</code></td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <!-- ── .gitignore ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="gitignore">A .gitignore for Machine Learning</h2>

  <p>
    Never commit model weights, datasets, or generated files. They bloat the repository
    and make it unusable for others who have different data paths.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename=".gitignore"
    code={`# ── Python ────────────────────────────────────────────────
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*.egg-info/
dist/
.venv/
.env

# ── Jupyter ───────────────────────────────────────────────
# Keep .ipynb source but strip outputs (use nbstripout)
.ipynb_checkpoints/

# ── ML artifacts ──────────────────────────────────────────
*.pt
*.pth
*.ckpt
*.pkl
*.h5
*.onnx
runs/
checkpoints/
outputs/
wandb/
lightning_logs/

# ── Data ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
data/
datasets/
*.csv
*.parquet
*.json.gz

# ── IDEs & OS ─────────────────────────────────────────────
.idea/
.vscode/
*.swp
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db`}
  />

  <!-- ── README ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="readme">Writing a README</h2>

  <p>
    A good README lets a new lab member reproduce your results without ever asking you
    a question. It is also the first thing your co-supervisors will read when reviewing
    your project. Treat it as part of your thesis work, not an afterthought.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock lang="markdown" filename="README.md" code={readmeExample} />

  <!-- ── Notebooks ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="notebooks">Jupyter Notebooks</h2>

  <p>
    Notebooks are great for exploring data and producing figures. They are poor for
    training logic because:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Cell execution order is invisible from the file — bugs hide easily.</li>
    <li>They generate enormous diffs when committed with outputs.</li>
    <li>They are hard to run in CI or to call from other scripts.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    <strong>Best practice:</strong> write core logic as Python modules in <code>src/</code>,
    import them in notebooks, and keep notebooks only for visualisation and reporting.
    Use <a href="https://github.com/kynan/nbstripout" target="_blank" rel="noopener">nbstripout</a>
    to automatically strip outputs before committing:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# Install nbstripout (inside the container, or in a local dev environment)
pip install nbstripout

# Configure it as a git filter for this repo (run once)
nbstripout --install`}
  />

  <!-- ── Coding Style ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="style">Coding Style</h2>

  <p>
    Consistent code style makes reviews faster and reduces cognitive overhead when
    reading others' work.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Language</th><th>Style Guide</th><th>Auto-formatter</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Python</td>
        <td><a href="https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PEP 8</a></td>
        <td><code>ruff format</code> or <code>black</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>C++</td>
        <td><a href="https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google C++ Style Guide</a></td>
        <td><code>clang-format</code></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Add <code>ruff</code> to your <code>requirements.txt</code> and run it as part of
    your Docker workflow:
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    code={`# Check for style issues
ruff check src/

# Auto-fix issues and format
ruff check --fix src/
ruff format src/`}
  />

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-green-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <path d="M22 11.08V12a10 10 0 1 1-5.93-9.14"/>
      <polyline points="22 4 12 14.01 9 11.01"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>The golden rule:</strong> if a colleague unfamiliar with your project can
      clone your repository and reproduce your main result following only the README —
      without asking you anything — your code quality is good enough.
    </div>
  </div>

</DocsLayout>
